children.name: Sep. 16 Questions: Does it matter left hand/right hand or just right hand Right now, the code is only for the right hand. But the interface will need to have the left hand tasks included as well. I think it's best if we start the design with that in mind. I say we focus on achieving the functionality for the right hand only (for the first design iteration) and then implement the left hand later - which will be easy, code-wise. But the design should accommodate for the left hand as well if possible. That means that probably the first prompt should include something like "which hand are you wanting to assess today? right? left? both?" Does the program detect if the patient is doing it correctly? The program doesn't know if the patient recorded the task correctly. And that's the difficult part. I think the best I can do in that case is to throw an error and ask the patient to rerecord if the hand wasn't recognized by the Leap for the entire 2 seconds. We can include that in the design. How long to hold the initial position (eg. palm facing camera) and then the 2s motion? Or does it matter the patient has to start from a initial position and do the motion, or just holding the position is fine? Right now the code starts a second after the last audio file is played. So that is when the timer starts and so does the data recording. They need to hold the hand in the required position for 2 seconds as indicated in the instructions (it might be longer in the future if we decide it's not enough time). Sep. 20 To do Update the User Flow Finish High-fidelity screens Create hand animation example Look into data visualization Unity Kit Try to implement the UI scenes on Unity

children.name: Defining Scope (Sep. 15th) Background After chatting with and observing several OTs and hand specialists, we realized that measuring certain aspects of patient's hand function can be a tedious and time-consuming task for clinicians. One of such hand function measures is a range of motion (ROM) - how much each finger joint can flex or extend. Right now, clinicians measure it with hand-held goniometers, which takes a lot of time, is prone to human error, and does not provide any visual feedback of the patient's progress. Problems The current method (hand-held goniometers) have these issues: Tedious and time-consuming Prone to human error Does not provide any visual feedback of the patient's progress. Why it’s important Measuring the function is important in: 1. Tracking progress 2. Understanding the effects of therapy 3. Incentivize insurance companies to continue paying for treatment. GOAL Develop an interface that would guide patients (or clinicians with their patients) to record different hand poses to estimate the ROM using commercially-available hand-tracking technologies like the Leap Motion Tracker. HMW statement How might we create a user-friendly and visually engaging interface that guides patients through hand assessments, provides clear instructions, and visualizes their progress to enhance their understanding of therapy outcomes using AR technology like Leap Motion Tracker? Design Requirements Patient Info Entry Input patient ID, diagnosis, provider, and date. Onboarding Visual and audio cues highlight interface areas and explain how tasks work (e.g., ensuring the status is green). Assessments Provide video and text instructions to guide patients through tasks. Improve video quality (consider animated hand demos) Include interactive elements eg. hand detection status, a timer to cue, completion feedback, proceed to next button, etc. Results Visualization Use line/bar graphs to display progress, with session numbers and dates. Allow users to select a date range to track metrics. Timeline
children.characters:
Defining Scope (Sep. 15th)

Background

After chatting with and observing several OTs and hand specialists, we realized that measuring certain aspects of patient's hand function can be a tedious and time-consuming task for clinicians. 

One of such hand function measures is a range of motion (ROM) - how much each finger joint can flex or extend. Right now, clinicians measure it with hand-held goniometers, which takes a lot of time, is prone to human error, and does not provide any visual feedback of the patient's progress.

Problems

The current method (hand-held goniometers) have these issues: 
Tedious and time-consuming
Prone to human error
Does not provide any visual feedback of the patient's progress.

Why it’s important 

Measuring the function is important in:
1. Tracking progress
2. Understanding the effects of therapy
3. Incentivize insurance companies to continue paying for treatment.

GOAL 

Develop an interface that would guide patients (or clinicians with their patients) to record different hand poses to estimate the ROM using commercially-available hand-tracking technologies like the Leap Motion Tracker.

HMW statement

How might we create a user-friendly and visually engaging interface that guides patients through hand assessments, provides clear instructions, and visualizes their progress to enhance their understanding of therapy outcomes using AR technology like Leap Motion Tracker?

Design Requirements

Patient Info Entry
Input patient ID, diagnosis, provider, and date. 

Onboarding
Visual and audio cues highlight interface areas and explain how tasks work (e.g., ensuring the status is green).

Assessments
Provide video and text instructions to guide patients through tasks. 
Improve video quality (consider animated hand demos)
Include interactive elements eg. hand detection status, a timer to cue, completion feedback, proceed to next button, etc. 

Results Visualization
 Use line/bar graphs to display progress, with session numbers and dates. 
Allow users to select a date range to track metrics.


Timeline
